Instructions


Data Versioning(10 Points)
This CLO assesses the group’s ability to use version control to manage, synchronise, and update project files collaboratively using GitHub.







1. Creating a Repository (1 Point)

 


Out in the open, a fresh GitHub spot called Group7 now holds every file tied to the project. Holding everything together, it gives the team a single location for documents while tracking changes as work moves forward.















2. Uploading Project Files (1 Point)

 




Files for the project now live on GitHub - reports, notebooks, everything needed sits together. With these in place, teammates reach what they need without hunting through scattered folders. Organization sticks when materials stay in one predictable spot.


3. Local Repository Setup (2 Points)


 

 

A folder appeared on the computer, pulled down by GitHub Desktop. Working without internet became possible since edits stayed saved nearby. Changes moved smoothly between people because each person kept a full copy close at hand.




4. Cloning the Repository (2 Points)
The GitHub repository is cloned locally to allow collaborative development and file versioning.


 

A fresh version landed on the machine after grabbing it straight from GitHub by pasting the web link. That local setup opened doors - teammates started adjusting code, swapping notes, pulling updates without roadblocks. 


5. Synchronising Changes (2 Points)
Updates from the remote GitHub repository are retrieved to ensure the local repository remains up to date.

 


Now pulling from the source, the team grabbed fresh updates through GitHub Desktop's fetch option. Staying current means their local copy matches what's live out there.
















6. Committing and Updating the Repository (2 Points)

 


Out of nowhere, someone tweaked the README file before pushing it to the repo. Each change got recorded, just like version tracking is supposed to work. Updates appear in order - no mess, no guesswork.

























Evidence for Assessment
The following may be used to support evaluation:
•	GitHub repository link
•	Commit history showing file updates and meaningful commit messages
•	Show screeshots of the acts.

At least one commit from a non leader group member is expected.



